  "prompt": "Is internal hard drive a primary storage device or secondary storage device?",
  "response": "Internal hard drive is considered a secondary storage device. Here's why:\n\n1. Primary storage devices (Primary memory):\n- RAM (Random Access Memory)\n- ROM (Read-Only Memory)\n- Cache memory\n- These are directly accessible by the CPU and provide temporary, fast storage for immediate processing.\n\n2. Secondary storage devices:\n- Hard disk drives (HDD)\n- Solid-state drives (SSD)\n- Optical drives (CD/DVD)\n- USB drives\n- These store data permanently and provide long-term, non-volatile storage that is not directly accessible by the CPU.\n\nSo, an internal hard drive is a secondary storage device because it:\n- Stores data permanently\n- Retains data even when the computer is turned off\n- Has larger storage capacity compared to primary memory\n- Provides slower access speeds compared to primary memory",
